<section class="hero">
  <div class="container hero-grid">
    <div class="hero-text">
      <div class="hero-eyebrow">
        <span class="plate">Plate 00 / Intro</span>
        <span class="dash" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <span class="tag">For agentic coding</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="pitch">
        How to write code when your compiler speaks <em>English</em>.
      </h1>

      <ol class="framing" aria-label="Three-line framing">
        <li>LID is the language.</li>
        <li>Claude is the compiler.</li>
        <li>Code is the output.</li>
      </ol>

      <p class="hero-lede">
        Modern coding agents rarely write bugs. What they write are <em>intent gaps</em> — places where the agent assumed one meaning and you held another. LID closes those gaps by giving your agent a <em>dialect</em> of English it can compile faithfully: specs are source, code is compiled output, and every intent change cascades downstream. A minimum system. Not a factory.
      </p>

      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="#quickstart">
          Install<span class="arr" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        </a>
        <a class="button" href="{{ site.repoUrl }}">
          On GitHub<span class="arr" aria-hidden="true">↗</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="hero-aside" aria-label="Arrow-of-intent schematic">
      {% include "hero-schematic.svg" %}
    </aside>
  </div>
</section>

